Part I - How Various loan data features affect borrowers APR¶

by (ThankGod Onmeje)¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. the loans were given by proser loan company

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

the extracted Data consists of 77557 rows and 7 columns including Term, ListingNumber, EmploymentStatus, DebtToIncomeRatio, StatedMonthlyIncome, LoanOriginalAmount, BorrowerAPR, ProsperScore etc.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in knowing What factors affect the borrowers APR (Annual percentage rate) and how?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I suspect the following factors will affect the borrowers APR:

  • Term
  • EmploymentStatus
  • DebtToIncomeRatio
  • StatedMonthlyIncome
  • LoanOriginalAmount
  • ProsperScore
  • BorrowerAPR

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

From the visual assessment the borrowerAPR seems to be multimodal with most of the values falling between 0.13-0.24. there also seem to be a hike somewhere around 0.37. there was no need for transformation on this column

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • The original data consists of 81 columns with some missing values. since i wouldn't need all 81 column I picked out the ones I needed for the analysis
  • for the loan amount most values in multiples of 5k how ever the most of the values fall betweeen 5k-15k
  • For debt to income ratio most values exists between 0.1-0.3 however a number of values exist on the 10.1 mark which could be explained by the fact that the values were capped at 10.1(ie. values above 10 were set to 10.1)
  • the monthly income of borrowers is seen to be rightly skewed. Less than 0.1 percent borrowers have stated monthly income greater than 40k, these can be seen as outliers, so I remove borrower records with income greater than 40k
  • I noticed there was outlier values on the monthly income column. dropped these values

In [44]:
# plot matrix of numeric features against categorical features using a box plot.

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x=x, y=y, color = default_color);

plt.figure(figsize = [10, 10])
g = sb.PairGrid(data = loan_sub, y_vars = ['BorrowerAPR', 'StatedMonthlyIncome', 'LoanOriginalAmount'], 
                x_vars = cat_cols, height = 3, aspect = 1.5);
g.map(boxgrid);
plt.xticks(rotation=30);

<Figure size 720x720 with 0 Axes>
  • The longer the loan term the more the loan amount
  • The lower the prosper score the higer the borrowers APR
  • The higer the prosper score the higer the monthly income
  • Borrowers who are employed and self-employed have more loan amount and monthly income compared to not employed or part-time

Some of the relationships I observed in this part of the investigation.¶

  • As the prosper score gets better the relationship between the loan amount and APR changes from negative to slightly positive
  • Borrowers with lower prosper score tend to have higher APR and less loan amount

Some interesting or surprising interactions between features¶

  • APR decreases with term for people with score of 4,6,7,8 while it increases for people with score of 1,9,10,11

Conclusions¶

The above analysis reveals some very interestng insights. Below are some key insights particularly related to my feature of interest- BorrowersAPR

  • The lower the prosper score the higher the APR
  • As the prosper score gets better the relationship between the loan amount and APR changes from negative to slightly positive
  • Borrowers with low prosper score have higher APR and less loan amount
  • The borrowers APR is generally negatively corrolated with the loan amount. ie. the more the loan amount the lesser the borrowers APR. However, for different range of loan amount there is a wide range of APR
  • The lower the prosper score the higher the APR
